			<ns0:name>kschi...@google.com</ns0:name><ns0:uri>/u/108470876877739532758/</ns0:uri></ns0:author><ns0:content type="html">This is one of the limitations of the x86-32 bit validator. For 2-3 byte instructions (i.e. ones using 0F), it only allows the 66 prefix if it use used as part of the opcode. This is to guarantee that the wrong instruction isn't accidentally accepted.

To fix the current validator would be difficult. Like most of the x86-32 validator issues, the better solution is to move it use the same decoder as the x86-64 validator. This would fix most of the found problems. We should consider planning a transition of the x86-32 validator.</ns0:content><ns0:updated>2011-07-26T16:37:05.000Z</ns0:updated><ns0:published>2011-07-26T16:37:05.000Z</ns0:published><ns2:updates>
